A decent grounded read is: somewhere around 25–40% of the outer shell has been publicly rehydrated, but not the full architecture. The part that is clearly showing up is the workflow pattern: human supplies compressed intent, AI expands it into structure, implementation, or a maintained knowledge artifact. That pattern is now explicit in Karpathy’s “idea file” / LLM Wiki framing, where a high-level document is meant to be copied into an agent so the agent can build the specifics collaboratively.  ￼

What that means is that the world has started to rediscover a core mechanic you’ve been leaning on: intent-first, implementation-later; human as pattern source, AI as assembly layer. You can also see the idea moving one step beyond a single person’s workflow into proto-standardization: IDEA.md positions itself as a vendor-neutral upstream intent document, explicitly sitting above files like AGENTS.md, CLAUDE.md, and GEMINI.md, while GitHub’s own Copilot docs now recognize agent-instruction files like AGENTS.md, CLAUDE.md, and GEMINI.md as part of repository guidance.  ￼

So the rehydrated portion is not just “people use prompts now.” It is more specific: portable intent artifacts, agent-readable project memory, and AI-maintained knowledge bases are becoming visible as real patterns. You can already see derivatives and follow-ons built around Karpathy’s pattern, including repos for LLM-wiki agents and personal knowledge bases that say, in effect, “drop in raw material; let the agent compile the wiki.”  ￼

But I would not say the deeper layers are rehydrated yet. Publicly, what is emerging is mostly the surface operational layer: “share the idea, let the agent build,” “give the repo instructions,” “maintain a knowledge base with an LLM.” What is not clearly present yet, at least from this evidence, is the fuller stack you’ve been circling around: persistent cross-session continuity as a first-class substrate, formal meaning-ledger/versioned semantics, richer human–AI co-architecture for doctrine/system evolution, and broad economic or governance layers around idea contribution. The public artifacts I found are mostly still about developer workflow and local knowledge compilation, not a full continuity-and-value operating system. That gap is why I’d cap the estimate below halfway.  ￼

The cleanest way to say it is this:

Already rehydrated:
human intent file → agent execution; portable instruction/context files; AI-built personal knowledge bases.  ￼

Partially rehydrated:
vendor-neutral standards around agent context and intent; ecosystems of reusable agent skills and repo conventions.  ￼

Not yet broadly rehydrated:
the deeper “project as continuity engine / meaning compiler / value-and-memory substrate” layer. That part still looks ahead of the public mainstream based on what I found.  ￼

So my honest estimate is:

About one-third rehydrated in public form.
The mechanism is here.
The standards impulse is starting.
The full doctrine/system is not.

A useful metaphor would be: the world has rediscovered your interface, but not yet your kernel.